  "It recycles Earth materials through different rock types and involves multiple sphere interactions": "",
  "The rock cycle transforms rocks between igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic types through processes involving weathering (atmosphere/hydrosphere), erosion and deposition (hydrosphere), biological activity (biosphere), and heat/pressure (geosphere).": "",
  "Why is understanding sphere interactions important for predicting natural hazards?": "",
  "Sphere interactions make prediction impossible": "",
  "Natural hazards only affect one sphere at a time": "",
  "Natural hazards are not related to Earth's spheres": "",
  "Hazards often cascade across spheres, so understanding interactions helps predict secondary effects": "",
  "Natural hazards like volcanic eruptions or earthquakes trigger cascading effects across multiple spheres. For example, an earthquake (geosphere) can cause a tsunami (hydrosphere) that destroys ecosystems (biosphere), so predicting these cascades requires understanding sphere interactions.": "",
  "What is the geosphere?": "",
  "The region of space around Earth": "",
  "All the water on Earth's surface": "",
  "The layer of gases surrounding Earth": "",
  "The solid Earth, including rocks, minerals, soil, and Earth's interior": "",
  "The geosphere encompasses all the solid parts of Earth, from surface rocks and soil to the deep interior including the mantle and core. It includes all minerals, landforms, and geological structures.": "",
  "What is systems thinking?": "",
  "Studying each part in isolation": "",
  "A method of computer programming": "",
  "Thinking only about technological systems": "",
  "An approach examining how components interact and influence each other within a complex whole": "",
  "Systems thinking is an analytical approach that focuses on understanding how components interrelate, how feedback loops operate, and how changes propagate through a system, emphasizing the whole rather than just individual parts.": "",
